Predicting Funny Super Bowl Ads

Devesh Dalmia

05/22

1 Intro

One of the things Superbowl is known for are the exclusive new ads released in-between the finals during the break. Millions of people tune in every year and there is quite a buzz regarding which company had the best ad/trailer. Companies end up spending millions making these ads, and they’re a hit or miss with the audience.

So I wanted to explore: Can we predict if a superbowl ad is going to be funny?

And if not, can we at least look into the factors that make a superbowl ad? Will adding chickens to my Volkswagen commercial increase its buzz and publicity? How funny will my ad be if I include politics? Etc, etc, etc.

To do this, I found a dataset on Kaggle that collected binomial data on superbowl commercials and certain variables. I’ve gone ahead and cleaned up the data beforehand with just relevant columns, and now let’s take a look at what we have.

3 Data Split

The first step in our machine learning process is to split our data so that we have enough datapoints for creating our model, but also for testing our model at the end to check the accuracy. Afterall, we need datapoints to feed into our model see if it makes predictions well.

set.seed(100)
# choosing 75% of the data to be the training data
data_split <- initial_split(data, prop = .75)
# extracting training data and test data as two seperate dataframes
datatrain <- training(data_split)
datatest <- testing(data_split)

4 Solo Model Testing

The first model which we are going to create, or rather a series of models, are simple logistic models where we predict our outcome, funny, based on just a single factor. We are going to use a loop to replace the variables in the model one-by-one and then after it is created, we will extract values and information and store it in a separate table.

4.1 Automating our model

#Log-odds to probability conversion universal function. 

logit2prob <- function(logit){
  odds <- exp(logit)
  prob <- odds / (1 + odds)
  return(prob)
}
b<-c("danger","celebrity","patriotic", "animals","show_product_quickly")

i = 1

df <- data.frame(variablename = character(),
 ints = integer(),
 stringsAsFactors = FALSE)



for (x in b){
  f <- as.formula(
    paste("funny", 
          paste(x, collapse = " + "), 
          sep = " ~ "))

  model1 <- glm(f, data=datatrain, family=binomial)
  pval <- summary(model1)$coefficients[2, 4]
  
  coe <- summary(model1)$coefficients[2, 1]
  prob <- logit2prob(coe)
  
  




  df = rbind(df, data.frame(x, model1$deviance, model1$null.deviance, model1$aic, pval, coe, prob))

  i = i+1

}

df

Above is the table containing values for deviance, null.deviance, AIC, p-values, and coefficients for each variable pitted against our response variable. The probability column is derived from the coefficients column where we apply the formula e^coe/[1+e^coe]

4.2 Let’s examine what it means

From the table above, if we judge our model on a 95% confidence interval, then the only variable that is significant is danger. The log-odds coefficient value for danger is 1.67 and when converted to our probability, is 0.84. That means it increases the probability of it being funny increases by 84% if our ad is dangerous or has elements of danger.

Surprisingly, if our ad has a celebrity then the probability of it being funny reduces by roughly 46%.

While it seems that we’ve done some great exploration so far and come up with an idea of what makes an ad funny vs. not funny, we can’t just stop there. Chances our, an ad doesn’t just have animals, or just politics, instead it has multiple factors.

Cook’s distance helps us see which and how many outliers we have. As you can see we have a few datapoints that pass our threshold to be considered normal. This was just to explore our data more. If we wanted, we can filter out these points and go through the models again to see if our accuracy improves. However since we don’t have as many datapoints as I would like ideally, we will choose to keep these datapoints and keep the model untouched.

5.8 Accuracy of the full model

pred = predict(model2, newdata=datatest, type="response")
pred = ifelse(pred >= .5, TRUE, FALSE)
accuracy <- table(pred, datatest[,"funny"])
cat("The percent accuracy of this model is:",
sum(diag(accuracy))/sum(accuracy))
The percent accuracy of this model is: 0.7377049

We have a very good accuracy percentage for this model, and it lies in line with the goodness-of-fit results we found earlier.

6 Variable Selection

With variable selection, we can focus on a model which only has the variables that are imporant in predicting our response variable. To do this, we will take the full model, as well as the minimum model, and perform stepwise regression. Stepwise regression will automatically filter out the variables for us.

6.1 Backwards stepwise

model3=glm(funny~., family = binomial, data = data)

set.seed(100)

min.model <-  glm(funny~ 1, family = binomial, data = data)

# Perform stepwise regression
model4 <- step(model3, scope = list(lower = min.model, upper = model3),
                  direction = "backward", trace = FALSE)
summary(model4)

We see that applying the forward stepwise regression also gave us the same model as before, which in turn gave us the same accuracy. This is not necessarily a bad thing. In fact having the same two variables chosen in two different variable selection process is a good indicator that these variables are important. The same results can be explained by the fact that our dataset isn’t very large to begin with, as its only seen with larger datasets that the variables in forward and backwars stepwise start to differ.

7 Conclusion

We evaluated a dataset that contained many variables to see if we can predict if an ad is going to be funny or not. We started off with testing each variable individually to understand the coefficients and how much of an impact it will have on our response variable. We then looked at the full model to help us explain what happens if we don’t do any ML, and just threw everything at the wall to see what sticks. The full model had an accuracy of approximately 73% which wasn’t too bad. We also failed to reject the null hypothesis that the model is a good fit, which is a great sign. Lastly we performed two types of variable selection where we reduced our model down to simply two variables.

We saw that the accuracy two hit. Compared to the previous model’s 73%, the newer models only had an accuracy of 72%. This can probably be explained by the random nature of our data. There are many things which we can try to do to increase our accuracy, one being using cook’s distance, which we measured earlier, to remove any outliers we have in our dataset. We can also look for more data to feed into our models (both training and testing purposes) to reduce randomness. Looking at the bigger picture, while our accuracy did go down technically (and that ideally isn’t supposed to be the case with variable selection), we only lost 1% at the expense of reducing the complexity of our model (which is just as important).
